I got a spiffy new Viki2 display from Panucatt Devices to go with the Re-ARM board I got through Kickstarter. I created this Thing to adapt the Viki2 on my Fabrikator.

I chose to mount the Re-ARM board and RAMPS on top of the PSU instead of behind the front panel, so this mount does not include any provision for that. This adapter re-uses the original front panel mounting holes, and is designed to use the original 2mm self-tapping screws.

You will need 4 M3 screws and nuts (preferably Nylocks) to mount the Viki2 to the adapter.

You will also need to cut some small sections of plexiglas from the panel to give clearance for the cables.

description.text:
The previous version of the concept got the massive rate of the interested. After sleeping over the night I thought the there is still many expensive components.

Here are two new concepts!
The drive has two options
1) normal gear pull but this makes the the unit wide, filament distance 23mm
2) pulling plates, like in the sewing machine, the filament distance 13 mm!!

The other new idea is to use the camshaft to manipulate filament feeding. Just rotating the cams and any combination is possible.

No more any sliding part nor high accuracy machinery needed.

The camshaft design is based on gray code binary mapping. This allows that only one filament feeding change happens at the time.

description.text:
This filament spool holder is a derivative of the 'filament spool holder - triangle frame by andrewfrueh. 
The triangle frame is a Huxley frame and uses Huxley feet. The frame can be made to any dimensions using different length threaded rods.
The spoke slots and bolt holes were modified for to be M6 size (6mm).

Bill of Materials Part ----------- Dimensions ----------- Description Printed parts
4 x frame_vertex_foot.stl - Feet and bottom vertexes of the support frame traingles
2 x frame_vertex_M6_and_M8.stl - Top vertex for support frame. Center hole is 8mm to accept the M8 Top support frame span
2 x spool-hub.stl - Houses the 608 bearings and connects the spokes
6 x spool-spoke_M6.stl Threaded rods
6 x Support frame triangle sides - M6 300 mm - To create the triangles for the frame. You can change the length of these to adjust the height of the frame. Just make the rods all the same length. Ensure the frame you create is tall enough to allow the spool assembly to freely rotate.
2 x Bottom support frame spans - M6 150 mm - To span between the two bottom corners of the frame triangle. These determine how far apart the frame triangles will be. You can change the size of these to suit the amount of filament you want to put on the spool. I'd recommend they are at least 150mm.
1 x Top support frame span - M8 150 mm - Spans the top of the frame triangle. Acts as an axle for the spool assembly bearings. Make this the same length as the two bottom support frame spans.
3 x Spoke spans - M6 85mm - Spans between the spokes to hold the filament. Can be substituted with M6 80mm bolts or pan-head set screws Other hardware
2 x 608 Bearing
18 x M6 Pan-head machine screw - 16 mm - (I used 20mm screws as that's what I had handy but 16mm recommended as they will fit better inside the hub)
32 x M6 Hex nut - Add flat washers for each if you like (I didn't bother). Used to connect the spokes to the hub and the feet and top vertices to the support frame rods.
6 x M8 Hex nut
2 x M8 Large Washers (Sometimes called 'repair washers'). - Used to stop the hub screw heads catching on the frame supports at the top. ) Print: 4 x frame-vertex-foot.stl
2 x frame_vertex_M6_and_M8.stl
6 x spool-spoke_M6.stl
2 x spool-hub_M6.stl Cut/Prepare:

Please, feel free to contact me if you have any suggestions, questions or comments and if you make one upload some pictures.

I just glue the bed on top of the plastic part that move back and forward so I stays in place. The legs I screw them with the screws from the CD burner and I print some washers so the screw are tighten enough and they give stability to the platform. I just follow the instruction on the website:
http://www.instructables.com/id/Pocket-laser-engraver/?ALLSTEPS and in this other one to have more references:

This thing uses the intersection of randomly rotated cubes to simulate a stone, and then creates a wall made from those stones using running bond. The maximum rotation angle changes the shape of the stone, with smaller values being more brick-like, and higher rotation angles looking like you stuffed whatever chipped granite was lying around into a wall. A master random seed saves your arrangement. The base size and mortar dimensions are customizable as well. A "z_compression" variable is used to compensate for higher rotation angles which would otherwise appear to "float" in the mortar. Edit (1MAR2014): You can now change the number of cubes used to make a block. A new parameter "power" rotates blocks less based on how many blocks are asked for. So you can add facets without getting chips of stone. Future fixes:
-I want to add circular columns to the ends, so that you can string them together in an artistically pleasing way, without gaps.

This is my N64,000 gaming emulator with this I can play games from Atari all the way up to Nintendo 64 and PS1 I have modeled all the parts my self to fit into an old (and Broken) Nintendo 64 system. I am using, and all the parts fit for, an ODROID-XU4. The Odroid makes it much easier and smooth for 4 players at once compared to a Raspberry pi 3.

I am Using Lakka as my emulation OS and that works great. When building this Hot glue gun was definitely my best friend to be sure my connections where tight and my USB ports were secure.
If anyone else would like to put there own spin on it I would be more then happy to see what you have in mind!
Please do not do this to a working Nintendo 64 system! It broke my heart enough for me to gut this non working system.

What you'll need:
A old Nintendo 64 system (preferably broken) and its hardware (screws)
ODROID XU4 W/ power supply
https://www.amazon.com/ODROID-XU4-Single-Board-Computer-Gigabit/dp/B0163GEA64

Slim 4-Port USB Data Hub like this one:
https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01CHYKV9Q?psc=1

(2) 1/2' 2-56 screws
(1) SPDT MOM-ON Switch
http://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/cw-industries/G-1132-0003/SW338-ND/161127

(2) 1/4' 4-40 Screws with nuts
(1) 1/2' 4-40 screw
28 AWG wire
Soldering Iron
Hot glue gun

LED 1.8V >5mA rating such as these:
https://www.digikey.com/products/en/optoelectronics/led-indication-discrete/105?k=led&k=&pkeyword=led&pv543=17&pv543=18&FV=114016f%2C11402b2%2C1140050%2C1140343%2C4fc0078%2C4fc0017%2C4fc0018%2C4fc005d%2Cffe00069&mnonly=0&ColumnSort=0&page=1&quantity=0&ptm=0&fid=0&pageSize=25
Unfortunately I could not find a Blue LED with this kind of rating. So I just attached as described bellow. If you use a 1.8V LED you can simply attach your LED to Pin 11 with a 360 ohm Resistor in series to the anode and the cathode of your LED to Ground. This would be the most optimal approach to a indication LED of when your board is powered on.

RJ-45 Jack similar in size to this:
http://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/te-connectivity-amp-connectors/5555162-1/A31419-ND/769563

power Jack similar size to this (9mm x 15 mm):
https://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/cui-inc/PJ-002A/CP-002A-ND/96962

I use the retro link USB controllers they work great to play the old games with the feel of playing the real system, but you can also use almost any USB controller (xbox, ps3 etc.)

Lakka OS: http://www.lakka.tv/get/linux/
Lakka works amazing with controller recognition I haven't had to configure any controller that I have plugged into it.
Follow the instructions on the LAKKA website to upload the ROMs. having the RJ-45 Ethernet port outside made it a dream for me to add and remove ROM files.

You will need a special bit to open the Nintendo 64 (posted above). Remove all the guts keeping all the screws. Be sure to safe the plastic LED display piece, the Gray cartridge flaps with the springs. and anything else you feel like you want to hold onto. Desolder USB Ports and use roughly 28-30 AWG wire to extend the usb ports out to the printed usb slots. or buy new USB terminals (they would be easier to solder) Everything placed as it should be I have used hot glue to hold the usb terminals secure in the slots and zip ties for strain relief. My USB hub sits under the raft. I would solder the other end of my switch to the same switch that is on the board to the correct terminals. I also Added a 5mA LED to pin 1(5V) and pin 2 (GND) with a 360 ohm resistor in series with the anode of the LED. This unfourtently always has a blue indicator light on my N64K I am working on some code to pull a GPIO to ground for a better indicator light than one that is always on. ALso be sure you are using a low current diode because a 10mA or higher diode could break the ODROID. Ethernet and dc jack soldered and glued to secure. Be sure you have the DC jack soldered to the correct polarization! The switch is screwed to the Switch_bottom print then glued in place to secure. The white and grey wire are then soldered to the switch on the odroid board The top I printed the gamepack hold downs to make more space inside the console yet still have the appearance of the Nintendo 64 Here is the 270 degree hdmi Adapter I added to route out my permanent HDMI cable. I did this so I would not be cutting into the plastic of the N64 to make any damage to the housing. I also had added MTA connections between my top switch and the switch on the board to make it easy to detach and rework if I ever need to.

description.text:
Fahrradhalterung für das Outdoor-Smartphone Archos Saphir 50.
Durch eine bewegliche Klappe vor dem Schalter lässt sich der sehr schwergänginge Schalter des Gerätes wesentlich leichter bedienen.
Die Lenkerhalterung ist für einen Lenkerdurchmesser von 25mm angelegt. Das entspricht dem mittleren Teil des Lenkers, die Halterung wird also über dem Vorbau (die Halterung des Lenkers) befestigt.
Sollte der Vorbau über dem Lenker mehr als 12mm Raum einnehmen, müssen die oberen Halterungsteile entsprechend angepasst werden.

Introduction - Anleitung

English:
You need a metal axis for the switch (1.5mm x 54mm), 4 screws (M4 x 40mm), 4 nuts (M4) and some glue to fix the switch axis. A little rubber should be placed between the handlebar and the bracket (for example, a piece of old bicycle hose).
Furthermore, I would recommend to glue the shell with the top attachment.

Deutsch:
Du brauchst eine Metall-Achse für den Schalter (1,5mm x 54mm), 4 Schrauben (M4 x 40mm), 4 Muttern (M4) und etwas Kleber zum fixieren der Schalterachse. Zwischen Lenker und Halterung sollte noch etwas Gummi platziert werden (z.B. ein Stück alter Fahrradschlauch).
Desweiteren würde ich empfehlen, die Schale mit den oberen Befestigungen zu verkleben.

title: FLSun I3 X Axis compatible with official Prusa mount

description.text:
This is a redesign of the Flsun i3 X gantry. It allows you to use the PrusaResearch I3 mk2 parts to mount your hotend, which in my opinion are better designed and include built in fan ducts for both the hotend and heat sink, and a mount for a capacitive bed sensor. You also get the option to use a standard extruder as well in order to use flexible filaments (the main reason I created this).

I've also remodeled the Prusa parts to allow use of the stock FLsun hotend with or without the bowden, which is an E3d v5 clone. Parts not included here are available from Prusa research.

If you want to use your stock FLSun hotend with your stock bowden extruder, you need to print the Xaxisprusamod.stl, the ExtrudermountBowden.stl, and the ExtruderMountCover.stl from here, and then print the fan-nozzle.stl from prusaresearch's official i3 mk2 files.

If you want to use your stock FLSun hotend with the prusa style direct-extruder, you need to print the Xaxisprusamod.stl, the ExtrudermountBase.stl, and the ExtruderMountCover.stl from here, and then print the fan-nozzle.stl and the Extruder-Idler.stl from prusaresearch's official i3 mk2 files.

To use an e3d v6 style hotend, you only need the Xaxisprusamod.stl. All other parts can be printed from the i3 mk2 files.

Xaxisprusamod.stl assembles the same as your flsun xaxis gantry but you don't add the fans.
After that, the Hardware is all M3 screws and assembles the same as the official version. You will need hex nuts and square nuts. All screws should be the same length as in the assembly guide for http://manual.prusa3d.com/Guide/5.+Extruder+Assembly/114. The dimensions should be nearly identical. The blower fan can be swapped over, its the right size, but the fan that comes with the flsun is 40mm. You can either swap it for a 30mm fan, or print a 30 to 40mm adaptor of thingiverse.

TO DO: The v5 hotend is slightly longer than the v6, at some point I'd like to extend this so the part cooling fan points at the part better. Works okay at the moment, will revisit when I have a few more prints with it to see what else I want to redesign.

Edit: Forgot to countersink a hole on the Extrudermountcover. Reuploaded correct file.
